<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-485-277  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 485 277.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Oct 1 1990 v36 n1829 p7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC would certify CPU boards for PCs. (the US FederalCommunications Commission proposes certification of CPU boards formicrocomputers without requiring type-approval for newconfigurations)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Federal Communications Commission (FCC) proposescertification of CPU boards for microcomputers to letmanufacturers and integrators switch boards without having to gettype-approval for all new configurations.andP;  FCC rules now in placeand intended to eliminate spurious emissions require thatmanufacturers receive separate approval for every microcomputerconfiguration sold to the public.andP;  CPU boards are consideredsubassemblies of the system itself and need not be certifiedthemselves, but microcomputers are marketed differently now, whichrequires changes in FCC treatment and testing procedures for CPUboards.andP;  The FCC suggested in a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking thatrules be modified to include CPU boards under definition ofperipheral devices, making them subject to the same testing andauthorization procedures as other Part 15 digital devices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electromagnetic RadiationGovernment AgencyTestingGovernment RegulationCertificationCPUBoards-CardsUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>